land-jobber
Homonym Number:
Word Class:noun
Sense Number:
Definition:
Origin:[none]
Register:
Register 2:
Domain:[none]
Region:[none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes: [AND 1835.] Although attested in English before, (a 1748 Swift-OED) not necessarily pejoratively, in NZ between 1839 and 1842 it was used almost as a popular (political or journalistic) catchphrase, mainly in a bad sense against the Official Government and Missionary party in Auckland, by the NZ Company settlers and colonists. It took on most of the connotation of land-shark. qv. The Bay of Islands and Auckland saw much early private speculation in land.
